President Trump gave a speech at the Department of Interior where he thanked Vice President Mike Pence for his service. He praised the department for their work in preserving America's natural resources and protecting the people's access to land. Trump highlighted the historic actions taken in the first 100 days of his presidency to eliminate regulations, returning power to the people. He signed an executive order to end the federal control of land and water under the Antiquities Act, giving power back to the states and the people. Trump mentioned the abuse of the monuments designation and the objection of citizens in Utah to the federal government's control over Bears Ears. He emphasized that the federal government should not have unlimited power to lock up land and water. Trump thanked Secretary Ryan Zinke and Senator Orrin Hatch for their support and efforts in bringing about this change. He concluded by saying that positive things will happen on America's incredible land.